WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.840
So I think if you're here at this conference and you're like me, probably you feel that R has a

00:00:12.840 --> 00:00:20.120
first-class place within any modern data science team, right? You know, kind of posit, use a lot

00:00:20.120 --> 00:00:26.040
of R, and that was most of my career. But the thing is, is that a lot of the time that decision is

00:00:26.040 --> 00:00:32.560
not really up to you. And you can find yourself in a position where the tools that you kind of know

00:00:32.560 --> 00:00:37.240
and love, actually you're prevented for whatever reason from using them to accomplish your goals,

00:00:37.240 --> 00:00:42.639
right? I wanted to start this out by talking about one of my kind of larger career mistakes,

00:00:42.639 --> 00:00:48.720
and aside from going to law school, this is maybe like my largest career mistake. Law school still

00:00:48.720 --> 00:00:57.040
ends. So I was hired by a company called Socure to build shiny apps and to improve their R tooling,

00:00:57.040 --> 00:01:02.080
right? R functions to help teach people to use R better, and I was good at that. And I was at

00:01:02.080 --> 00:01:06.080
Socure during this, I was lucky enough to be there during a time of really extraordinary growth. So

00:01:06.080 --> 00:01:12.400
this company hit right at the right time and doubled revenue basically every year for about

00:01:12.400 --> 00:01:18.320
three years. And with that growth came one important challenge, which is that in order to, the way our

00:01:18.320 --> 00:01:23.040
business was structured, every sort of marginal increase in revenue required more and more data

00:01:23.040 --> 00:01:28.279
scientists. So by the end I think we were hiring something like 40 a year. And finding data

00:01:28.279 --> 00:01:32.720
scientists who knew something about identity fraud and also were good enough at R was very difficult.

00:01:32.720 --> 00:01:37.160
So the company at some point decided that we're gonna standardize on Python to have access to a

00:01:37.160 --> 00:01:42.760
larger hiring pool. Right around this time my boss came up to me and said, Gordon, you know, I love

00:01:42.760 --> 00:01:47.360
the work you've done with with R, can you do the same thing with Python? What I should have said

00:01:47.360 --> 00:01:53.040
was, yes, of course, it's Python. You know, it's not that far away. I know this problem domain very well.

00:01:53.040 --> 00:01:59.160
I feel like I have a good intuition about how people analyze data. I can do that. But I didn't do that.

00:01:59.160 --> 00:02:06.519
I didn't do it because I had a lot of doubt about my own intuition about how to build good Python

00:02:06.519 --> 00:02:11.960
tools, and just kind of like a basic lack of familiarity. My R skills were so good at that

00:02:11.960 --> 00:02:19.039
point that whenever I tried using Python I felt like I was all thumbs. And since then I've kind of

00:02:19.039 --> 00:02:23.080
been wondering, like, what was it, you know, that prevented me from having that confidence? Like,

00:02:23.080 --> 00:02:27.199
what was it that I didn't have? Of course, my whole career people have been telling me to learn

00:02:27.199 --> 00:02:33.759
Python. And I tried. I'd taken online courses, built little projects, etc., etc. And I think there's a

00:02:33.759 --> 00:02:37.800
couple of reasons why it's really difficult, or why I found it really difficult. The first one is

00:02:37.800 --> 00:02:42.960
that this goal is just absolutely terrible advice. Learn Python in the generic sense is a terrible

00:02:42.960 --> 00:02:48.000
advice. Because of course there are many Pythons. You know, like, you talk to somebody who's a data

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:53.000
scientist and they say the important skill is pandas. You talk to somebody else who is a, you

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:58.679
know, does a web serving project in Python and they'll tell you that pandas is a horrible dependency

00:02:58.679 --> 00:03:03.880
that'll ruin your life, right? So it doesn't really have any particular meaning. And because it doesn't

00:03:03.880 --> 00:03:07.399
have any particular meaning, you don't know the answer to a lot of these questions. When are you

00:03:07.399 --> 00:03:12.240
done? You know, what particular value does that provide to you in the short term? And how do you

00:03:12.240 --> 00:03:17.639
prove it, right? And all these things kind of prevent you from making progress, right? It's not a good

00:03:17.639 --> 00:03:25.360
goal. Secondly, R and Python are extremely close substitutes. They do, especially in the data

00:03:25.360 --> 00:03:29.839
science space, they do almost identical things. You know, we just heard that from Plot9, right? You

00:03:29.839 --> 00:03:35.399
have ggplot in R, Plot9 in Python, right? They're substitutes. You can do the same thing with them.

00:03:35.520 --> 00:03:40.960
And I would say for almost every task that you can point me to in Python, I can say I can do it in R and vice

00:03:40.960 --> 00:03:47.320
versa, right? And the cost of that, what that means is that there's this incredible awkwardness when you're

00:03:47.320 --> 00:03:52.160
trying to learn something that's almost exactly like what you already know, right? Because you're using it

00:03:52.160 --> 00:03:55.720
and you feel like you should already know how to do this thing, right? They're close enough that you feel

00:03:55.720 --> 00:04:03.080
like you should know it, but they're far enough away that you really don't, right? And because they're such

00:04:03.119 --> 00:04:08.679
close substitutes, in the short run, it doesn't feel valuable. You don't get that feedback that you get when

00:04:08.679 --> 00:04:12.199
you first start programming or when you start programming in a language that's truly different from

00:04:12.199 --> 00:04:17.600
one you know, which is that I have gained some new ability that I didn't have before. So I learned, my

00:04:17.600 --> 00:04:22.000
second language was actually React Native when I wrote a mobile application, and that was easy to learn,

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:26.119
right? Because I was able to sort of do something I couldn't do before, write something that goes on

00:04:26.119 --> 00:04:32.320
somebody's phone, you know, that was amazing. Can't do that in R, couldn't do it in R. So there's a lot of

00:04:32.320 --> 00:04:36.839
different ways of kind of coming up with a better goal for learning these systems. Like you often hear

00:04:36.839 --> 00:04:42.959
SMART, like Specific Something Something Actionable, I can never remember. Lots of different acronyms. But

00:04:42.959 --> 00:04:47.839
the one I kind of gravitate towards is really simple, which is, you might call this like value-based

00:04:47.839 --> 00:04:51.600
learning. And really what this means is that you need something, whenever you're learning a new

00:04:51.600 --> 00:04:58.440
thing, you need to find the part of that thing that provides you with real value really quickly. When I

00:04:58.440 --> 00:05:03.480
say real value, this is, I think, crucial, right? A lot of times when you learn a new thing, you use a toy

00:05:03.480 --> 00:05:10.200
example or one that's provided by the sort of generic way of educating a shelf, and it doesn't

00:05:10.200 --> 00:05:14.079
really kind of do the job, because you're not really stressing your understanding of it. You're not

00:05:14.079 --> 00:05:18.600
trying to accomplish a goal that you personally care about. So real value here, I think, usually

00:05:18.600 --> 00:05:24.000
means, in a work context, something that generates money or saves time. And it doesn't necessarily

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:27.839
need to be that, but most of the time that's what it is. So picking a part of that project where

00:05:27.839 --> 00:05:32.480
you're able to show that to somebody else in your life, your boss or your co-worker, and they're

00:05:32.480 --> 00:05:36.839
impressed. They see that there's some value for themselves and their organization. And the second

00:05:36.839 --> 00:05:41.640
thing is that you need to have that part where you realize that value extremely quickly. I think in a

00:05:41.640 --> 00:05:46.799
matter of weeks, you should be able to take something from that educational experience, show

00:05:46.799 --> 00:05:51.000
someone else, and justify the time that you've spent on it. I don't know about yourself, but I have a

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:56.600
fairly busy job and two young children, and all of my time is spoken for. So I need something where it

00:05:56.640 --> 00:06:02.279
gives me that value right away. So why is Shiny for Python a good option under this framework? I think

00:06:02.279 --> 00:06:06.279
there's three reasons, and this is what most of this talk is going to be about. Shiny for Python is the

00:06:06.279 --> 00:06:11.440
thing if you're an R developer, you want to diversify your career, don't end up like Gordon, have

00:06:11.440 --> 00:06:15.640
something where you're in your back pocket if you ever end up in this situation. Shiny for Python is

00:06:15.640 --> 00:06:19.559
the ideal thing to do. There's three reasons for this. The first is that it gives you something that

00:06:19.559 --> 00:06:25.160
you don't have. The second is that it's better than other Python web application frameworks. And

00:06:25.160 --> 00:06:34.200
finally, you already mostly know it. So what do you get? And I should specify here that the R Shiny

00:06:34.200 --> 00:06:40.359
application framework is not going anywhere. It's the leader on our team. It's where features probably

00:06:40.359 --> 00:06:46.959
land first and are going to land first for a while. And we have a huge community of R users, people

00:06:46.959 --> 00:06:51.399
who are building Shiny, R Shiny applications in incredible ways, doing incredible extensions. So

00:06:51.399 --> 00:06:54.880
those aren't going anywhere. So feature-wise, it's not like you get a bunch of features that you don't

00:06:54.880 --> 00:07:00.959
have in R. But you do get a couple of things. So the first one is you get much easier deployment in

00:07:00.959 --> 00:07:05.040
various different entities, right? So this is something that, over my career as a Shiny developer,

00:07:05.040 --> 00:07:10.640
has come up again and again and again, which is I build something that's useful, great even,

00:07:10.640 --> 00:07:15.279
impressive, and then you kind of go to deploy it, and you run into all kinds of barriers. And these

00:07:15.279 --> 00:07:20.119
apps, these undeployed apps that live on my laptop, mostly worthless, right? And R deployments are a

00:07:20.119 --> 00:07:26.519
little bit fraught, right? Because it's a niche language. It's often adding a dependency to any of

00:07:26.519 --> 00:07:30.679
your deployment environments. And that can be pretty difficult. So you get into a lot of these

00:07:30.679 --> 00:07:35.320
questions. And whether you think these questions are right or wrong, valid or invalid, they're things

00:07:35.320 --> 00:07:38.920
that people believe and that prevent you from deploying your apps, right? DevOps doesn't know how to

00:07:38.920 --> 00:07:43.839
use R. Will this scale? What happens if you leave? Who will I hire to do this? Right? Shiny for

00:07:43.839 --> 00:07:49.480
Python doesn't really have these problems because it's a kind of, it's built on foundational Python

00:07:49.480 --> 00:07:55.559
web application frameworks. So people will at least think that they can deploy it and manage it,

00:07:55.559 --> 00:07:59.480
right? Because a DevOps person will look at it and say, oh, it's just a Python, it's an ASGI Python

00:07:59.480 --> 00:08:04.359
application. I can probably handle that, right? In a way that when you're trying to deploy an R

00:08:04.359 --> 00:08:10.279
application of any kind, you can kind of often run into those problems. Second reason is that it's

00:08:10.279 --> 00:08:17.239
much easier to integrate into Python, the Python ecosystem. And especially over the last year, you've

00:08:17.239 --> 00:08:21.799
seen just so many incredible things that have come out of Python frameworks, large language models,

00:08:21.799 --> 00:08:26.519
things like that. And, well, it's, you can integrate these things with something like

00:08:26.519 --> 00:08:32.039
Reticulate in a lot of way, a lot of the time, like 95% of the time, that 5% of the time can be really

00:08:32.039 --> 00:08:37.719
painful, right? So, because Reticulate runs Python in R, so it's adding like two layers of things on

00:08:37.719 --> 00:08:43.080
top of your framework. You can kind of end up in these edge cases that are pretty difficult. Not

00:08:43.080 --> 00:08:47.640
everything works. Environments can be challenging. And especially if you're working in industry,

00:08:47.640 --> 00:08:51.640
it's very hard to get help. If you're having trouble installing somebody's kind of internal

00:08:51.640 --> 00:08:56.119
janky Python package and they come over to your desk and you're like, hey, I'm trying to install

00:08:56.119 --> 00:09:00.200
it in R, like whether it's the R's problem or their's problem, they're going to say it's R's

00:09:00.200 --> 00:09:05.400
problem, right? So having something where you just have a single language at runtime is really helpful

00:09:05.400 --> 00:09:11.000
for integrating those things. One language is simpler. And the final thing is it proves that

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:16.440
you know Python. And this is something that I think is really unique about building web applications,

00:09:16.440 --> 00:09:21.799
is that they serve as a kind of visual proof to other people and to yourself that you know how to

00:09:21.799 --> 00:09:27.640
provide value in Python, right? Even if your code is not the best, right? Even if you don't feel like

00:09:27.640 --> 00:09:33.080
you really know how you do it, the fact of the existence of that artifact is a way of sort of

00:09:33.080 --> 00:09:38.599
proving to other people in your life that, yeah, you know how to do this, right? And validating it for yourself.

00:09:41.080 --> 00:09:46.200
And the thing about that proof is that I really do think that the thing that you will produce,

00:09:46.200 --> 00:09:50.359
especially if you're somebody who has a little bit of experience with Shiny for R, is going to be

00:09:50.359 --> 00:09:55.239
really impressive to somebody who's looked only at Python web application frameworks. Because I

00:09:55.239 --> 00:10:00.200
think Shiny is better. And this is something that I'm probably saying in a little more stark way

00:10:00.200 --> 00:10:05.559
than I have said in other contexts. And better, of course, means different things to different people.

00:10:05.559 --> 00:10:09.559
But my work on the Shiny for Python team right now, I wouldn't be doing that if I didn't think

00:10:09.559 --> 00:10:14.119
it was the best, right? So I just wanted to clarify what do I mean by better? And for this

00:10:14.119 --> 00:10:21.400
I have another story. Which is after we made this transition to Python, we put together

00:10:21.400 --> 00:10:27.640
a web API that was for people to navigate our machine learning feature store.

00:10:27.640 --> 00:10:32.440
Like, get information about features, change them, et cetera, et cetera. It's a great important thing of

00:10:32.440 --> 00:10:36.520
centralizing this thing that we dealt with all the time. It caused a huge amount of friction.

00:10:36.599 --> 00:10:40.679
And it needed a front end. And we sort of looked around and said, okay, well, we're a Python shop

00:10:40.679 --> 00:10:45.799
now, how are we going to build this front end? And, you know, looked at various different options

00:10:45.799 --> 00:10:50.119
and the decision was, like, we're going to do it in React. We're going to build it in a, you know,

00:10:50.119 --> 00:10:54.039
there's going to be a web application and JavaScript front end, you know, be super pro, right?

00:10:54.039 --> 00:11:00.039
Wouldn't have any React developers on the team. So this implied hiring. And hiring implied budget.

00:11:00.039 --> 00:11:06.359
And budget implied approval. And ten months later we still didn't have this kind of value,

00:11:06.359 --> 00:11:11.239
realized. We didn't have the product, right? And that's the thing that I really hate personally,

00:11:11.239 --> 00:11:15.880
as whenever I've worked on a data science team, is that I want my team to be able to deliver

00:11:15.880 --> 00:11:20.039
the whole project, right? I don't want to have the situation where we built the model, we built the

00:11:20.039 --> 00:11:25.719
API, we did something, and then there's another team that we have to wait on or get cajole or get

00:11:25.719 --> 00:11:31.159
approval or get roadmap space to finish the project and actually show it to the user, right? I want to

00:11:31.159 --> 00:11:35.719
have something where we can do the whole thing, right? This is what Shiny does and I think what

00:11:35.719 --> 00:11:41.799
makes Shiny so special. So the way I kind of talk about this is an idea that you might call

00:11:41.799 --> 00:11:46.919
programmatic range, right? It's a framework that can do a lot of things and can do it smoothly.

00:11:47.640 --> 00:11:50.840
And a lot of the other web application frameworks that you talk about, they sort of say like, look,

00:11:50.840 --> 00:11:54.440
we can do simple things, we can do complicated things, but when you dig in, you realize that

00:11:54.440 --> 00:11:58.840
they're doing the simple thing and the complicated thing in totally different ways, right? It's almost

00:11:58.840 --> 00:12:02.200
as if they're like several frameworks in a trench coat, you know? And there's like, you have this

00:12:02.200 --> 00:12:05.559
simple thing and then like, oh, you're a little more complicated, like, let's learn a whole new

00:12:05.559 --> 00:12:08.679
pattern and you're a little more complicated than that, oh, we're gonna do a whole new thing, right?

00:12:08.679 --> 00:12:13.479
And Shiny is not like that. Shiny has the same pattern for every single Shiny app, reactivity,

00:12:13.479 --> 00:12:19.000
right? So if you know it, I taught a workshop on Saturday, the things that we taught them that day,

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:23.000
first time people experiencing Shiny, those are the same things that are done in the most

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:28.679
complicated Shiny apps. And so Shiny has this ability to serve you from very, very simple

00:12:28.679 --> 00:12:33.719
things to very, very complicated things. So that means for like that API example, if we wanted to

00:12:33.719 --> 00:12:37.960
build a prototype in Shiny just to get us to that 10 months until we have that React developer who

00:12:37.960 --> 00:12:42.359
can build something real, you know, that works, right? It's fast enough to do that, easy enough

00:12:42.359 --> 00:12:46.520
to do that. But if it turns out we actually don't want to hire that person or we can't,

00:12:47.080 --> 00:12:51.559
that prototype can smoothly grow into the product and Shiny has all the tools for doing it.

00:12:51.559 --> 00:12:54.599
So you don't need to hire anyone, right? That's my kind of definition of better, I guess.

00:12:55.320 --> 00:13:01.159
And so I just kind of wanted to give a little bit of a, there's about 20 different Python web

00:13:01.159 --> 00:13:03.080
application frameworks, so I'm not going to go through all of them, but I wanted to go through

00:13:03.080 --> 00:13:07.320
the ones that I've sort of seen being most commonly used in the businesses that I've talked to.

00:13:09.320 --> 00:13:13.080
So Streamlet is a very popular one, it's a wonderful language, it's optimized for, a wonderful

00:13:13.080 --> 00:13:18.520
framework, it's optimized for very, very simple applications. And that's kind of their load stars,

00:13:18.520 --> 00:13:23.880
like let's get the simple stuff to work and we will go, we will sacrifice anything for that goal,

00:13:23.880 --> 00:13:29.000
and the way they've done this is by running the entire script from top to bottom on every user

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:33.239
interaction. So this is a little bit like if you're running a parameterizer or a markdown

00:13:33.239 --> 00:13:38.359
or something like that, where every time anything changes, the whole thing runs, right? And if you

00:13:38.359 --> 00:13:42.599
think about this, that probably seems pretty inefficient, it is, and that's because it's

00:13:42.599 --> 00:13:47.000
sort of where their design space is, it's very, very close to this beginner experience of getting

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:52.679
something working. But this means that complex apps, in my opinion, are not really possible,

00:13:52.679 --> 00:13:57.159
right? Like at some point you reach this cliff with Streamlet where you have to throw it away,

00:13:57.159 --> 00:14:02.119
right? And you cannot grow into a product at some point, right? Not to say you can't do

00:14:02.119 --> 00:14:05.960
impressive things with it, but there's a sort of line where it doesn't work. And simple things

00:14:05.960 --> 00:14:09.479
are oddly difficult, like updating a slider, changing a button color, these things require

00:14:09.479 --> 00:14:17.080
JavaScript or at least state management. Dash is built around this idea of statelessness,

00:14:17.080 --> 00:14:22.039
and what that means is that each graph and table and component of your application

00:14:22.039 --> 00:14:26.280
has to be able to do everything independently. It's very difficult to share data between these

00:14:26.280 --> 00:14:31.640
two things. So if you had CSV that generated 20 plots, a kind of usual way of accomplishing that

00:14:31.640 --> 00:14:38.119
in Dash, not the only way, but a usual way, is to have that CSV be read in for each plot 20 times,

00:14:38.119 --> 00:14:42.200
right? And you can sort of share data, but it involves caching it in the browser or storing it

00:14:42.200 --> 00:14:47.640
into a database and having it reread and lots of things like that. So this is like if you imagine

00:14:47.640 --> 00:14:52.760
Shiny without reactive expressions or any reactive value or server state, it would kind of

00:14:52.760 --> 00:14:57.080
be something where it's like pretty flat experience, right? You don't have this idea of like caching an

