intermediary value and using it in many places. This is important. It does solve an important

00:15:01.960 --> 00:15:06.440
problem, which is Dash apps are incredibly easy to scale horizontally. You can have one app be

00:15:06.440 --> 00:15:11.159
served by many processes on a server or even many servers, so that's it's really good. My guess is

00:15:11.159 --> 00:15:17.159
that I've never had that problem. I'm not sure that many people actually do. And finally, these are

00:15:17.159 --> 00:15:22.200
kind of the Django, Flask, FastAPI, the sort of combination of an API layer that's written in

00:15:22.200 --> 00:15:28.760
Python with some front end. This is really good for many kind of larger applications, very steep

00:15:28.760 --> 00:15:35.000
learning curve, and you need to write and maintain your own front end. So the last reason, so those

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:40.200
are kind of what you get, right? You get to do something you can't do, and you give your boss or

00:15:40.200 --> 00:15:45.799
your company something that they can't do. But the cost side is also really low, because I think most

00:15:45.799 --> 00:15:50.440
of the people who are kind of familiar with R Shiny actually already know Shiny for Python. And

00:15:50.440 --> 00:15:55.159
the reason is that when you kind of are learning Shiny, you feel like you're learning an R package,

00:15:55.159 --> 00:15:59.719
right? Because there's only an R package. But most of the concepts and things that you're actually

00:15:59.719 --> 00:16:04.760
dealing with are sort of generic parts of the components. So you can think about Shiny and

